The paper deals with a problem of detecting and tracking multiple targets in a multipath environment, which involves handling high-dimensional estimation of latent variables. This suggests that the paper may belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category, which deals with the fundamental limits of data compression, communication, and processing. Additionally, the paper proposes a novel joint detection and tracking algorithm based on variational Bayesian inference, which involves probabilistic modeling and inference. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories, which deal with the development of algorithms and models for intelligent systems. Furthermore, the paper deals with the problem of tracking targets with unknown association relationships among measurements and propagation paths, which involves control and estimation of dynamical systems. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper presents simulation results of over-the-horizon radar multitarget tracking, which involves processing and analysis of visual data. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) sub-category.
